    },
    {
      "id": "7cc54efdd6fe6cbac68e0bf697982df8e3c6d1ab",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 257,
        "name": "Keith Mannthey",
        "email": "keith.mannthey@intel.com",
        "username": "kmannth",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-01-05 02:17:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI guess the question is should the spots that been \"secretly (un)writable \" become truly unwritable.  This patch makes them fully writable regardless if in makes logical sense to expose the underlying variables to user interaction.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9fff59ff8e87fb59424b43b6790480d8681afa6a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-05 02:26:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWe only add write permissions for root and only for the stats files.  It makes sense to allow write for these files since writing to them clears the relevant counters.  Technically we are not increasing functionality since root could open these files for writing regardless of their modes.  The point is to use the mode to give a hint to admins.  The only place where I remove write permission in in the case of srpc_rules which does not implement a write method.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
